04581nam a22006855i 9780226385686DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263856867 a10.7208/97802263856862doi  a(DE-B1597)525075  a(OCoLC)957525275  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aML3465b.L85 2017 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a784.1888509822231 aLuker, Morgan James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Tango Machine :bMusical Culture in the Age of Expediency /cMorgan James Luker. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b3 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in Ethnomusicology00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: On the Values of Music in Expedient Argentina -- t1. Expedient Soundings: The Genre Culture of Contemporary Tango Music -- t2. Contemporary Tango and the Cultural Politics of música popular -- t3. Tango among the Nonprofit Arts -- t4. Tango as Part of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity -- t5. "This Is Going to Be Good for All of Us": Tango and the Cultural Industries -- tConclusion: He Sings Better Every Day: Musical Culture in the Age of Expediency -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Argentina, tango isn't just the national music-it's a national brand. But ask any contemporary Argentine if they ever really listen to it and chances are the answer is no: tango hasn't been popular for more than fifty years. In this book, Morgan James Luker explores that odd paradox by tracing the many ways Argentina draws upon tango as a resource for a wide array of economic, social, and cultural-that is to say, non-musical-projects. In doing so, he illuminates new facets of all musical culture in an age of expediency when the value and meaning of the arts is less about the arts themselves and more about how they can be used. Luker traces the diverse and often contradictory ways tango is used in Argentina in activities ranging from state cultural policy-making to its export abroad as a cultural emblem, from the expanding nonprofit arts sector to tango-themed urban renewal projects. He shows how projects such as these are not peripheral to an otherwise "real" tango-they are the absolutely central means by which the values of this musical culture are cultivated. By richly detailing the interdependence of aesthetic value and the regimes of cultural management, this book sheds light on core conceptual challenges facing critical music scholarship today.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aPopular musiczArgentinaxHistory and criticism. 0aTangoszArgentinaxHistory and criticism. 4aArgentina. 4acultural development. 4acultural industries. 4acultural policy. 4aexpediency of culture. 4amanagerial regimes. 4amusic history. 4apopular music. 4atango. 4aurban change. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226385686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226385686.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles